As a writer, I need to be to use languages for translation in my stories. Most of the languages are in English. But some are not. 
Take Hebrew for instance. 
You type in a word and what do you get? The translation comes in Hebrew script. I can't read Hebrew. So it's worthless to me. Then you have the Asian languages that give you a phonetic spelling - but it's not how the word looks in English. Like the word phonetic - it would look fuhnetik, if actually spelled phonetically. Which would be wrong and of no use to me as a writer for those languages. 
They need to tweak it more in that regard for all the languages across the board - not just for us English gents. 
Then I would give this app a full 5üåü

I test-drove this app for about a half hour.  I would have used it longer but I too ran up against the one-and-done bug that seems to plague so many other iPhone users.  My remarks are chiefly about the German voice translation.  I found Google Translate to be good at translating the kind of stock phrases you might need in a phrasebook, like "Wie geht's" and "wieviel kostet das?" but for anything more complicated, there was a high degree of gibberish.  For instance, the phrase "dieser Tat ist ihnen immer noch ferner als die fernsten Gestirne," which should be rendered as something like "This deed is even farther from them than the furthest stars," comes back as "diesel cat is even and now farther window stars."  A common vulgar formula was rendered as "leak time to my [butt]".  As far as the text input goes, it's basically the same as the Google Translate webpage, but without the ability to correct the suggested translation, which for the languages I tested (each of German, Norwegian, and Turkish to English and vice versa) was okay but not perfect.
Translation of words is on point but playing voice acts up at times other than that its a must have app!

The app doesn't establish a connection to the voice recognition. 

Users, to fix this, double tap the home button. Look for the Translate app in the bottom menu, press and hold until it starts shaking, and then press the "X" on the icon. 

This ends the app and removes it from the temporary memory banks. 

Start the app up and continue using it again.

Note: You must be connected to the Internet to use this app.

column9: READ B4 U DOWNLOAD or you will dislike this app
column10:
This is a very useful app for those of us that need assistance with other languages.  However,  if you minimize (switch to another app or phone) the microphone will stop working (for voice transcripts).  You do NOT have to delete the app or restart your phone like other post say.  

If you minimize your app, you will have to turn it off from the background app tray (not sure the correct name for it) 

From the main screen double click the home key and the app tray window will open with all apps running in the background. Hold your finger down on the iTranslate app until is starts shaking.  Then click the X to close (not delete) the app.  

You can then reopen the app and start using the mic again.  

Let's hope the mighty Google fixes this problem soon.

column9: Novel, but not designed for actual use.
column10:
As far as it goes, this review only applies to English-Japanese-English.

This translator is good for novelty, and workable if there's a bilingual person with you at all times, but otherwise it's only helpful as a brainstorming tool. And even then only when it's used in conjuction with another, better dictionary.  Furigana only appear if you look up a word in a very particular way. A search for one English word often yields six to ten Japanese words, completely without explanation or context. Fine if you already know all thre words, but a translation tool needs to be more than a memory aide.

The lack of a jump function is obvious and unforgiveable. Truly, this is the hotmail of translation apps.

This is a 5-star app when online.  0-star app offline.  I averaged it to 3-stars.  Using an iPhone 3GS.

I use Google Translate for Spanish translation between US & Mexico manufacturing facilities and it is very helpful.  This app is advertised that you can at least view your favorite translations and translation history offline, which is more helpful than no translation at all I suppose.  However, I have yet to get the app to start offline, let alone actually access my fav's or history.  Anyone who ever encounters lack of a decent cell phone signal may be disappointed.  Especially if translation is something you rely on.  Google Translate Support was no help.  It may work on phones other than my iPhone 3GS.

Speech recognition of English works very well for me.  The playback of translations is excellent.  It sounds just like someone is actually speaking and not a computerized voice.  Accuracy of translation is usually very good, although not always perfect.  Most often, it is comprehendible and we are able to communicate.  I am trying to learn to speak Spanish and find this to be one of my most useful and often used tools...as long as I have an internet connection.

I initially downloaded Word Lens after it featured in the IPhone advert. With that you pay ¬£5.99 per language and then it doesn't work. I did a bit of research into the best translator app and found out about this one and I love it. 

You can type or paste the text you want translated. Then you chose the language you want it translated from and to from the extensive list. It then displays the translation, offers you the chance to blow it up to full screen size (to show the person) or with nearly all languages there is a speech option whereby the translated text can be spoken aloud through your loudspeaker/headphones in the translated language. So you have three options, try to say the phrase yourself, have the app speak the phrase, or just blow up the text to let the person read it for themselves which is particularly nice if it is in Arabic or Chinese for example. 

All this and it's free!!!!
Now THIS is the 21st Century!

column9: Speech functionality is good in english. Not so for anything else.
column10: Don't get me wrong. I love the idea behind this app. But if you try translating (speech) anything not in english, it seems speech recognition fails miserably to the point of being absolutely useless. My native langage is French, and I was never able to make it recognize ANY word I'm saying let alone complete sentences. Works great for text translation, but the speech recognition is completely useless for me, which is why this app would've been great in the first place. Wonderful idea... Just a shame that it doesn't work right for all languages...

I like the functionality of the app - which never seems to crash.

The 'read-aloud' function is good, with generally accurate pronunciation, but could benefit from processing longer phrases/sentences.

The translation is generally inaccurate, however, is good considering the stage of translation technology. 

Overall, this is app is useful, but should be 'taken with a pinch of salt' and is not appropriate for direct translation.

column9: The best translation app using Google Translate, and includes audio
column10:
Google has made the best translation app that uses their own online service (most apps use Google Translate). It is very clean and efficient in it's appearance, easy to use, tells you whether audio is available for the chosen languages, and audio is available without additional purchase (the languages I use have local accents). You can translate from audio, which is reasonably accurate. Single word translations include grammatical variants. 

What's missing. You can't enter a URL to translate a web-page; but you can do this using the Google app, which has a link to the Translate web-site. There are no quick-link sharing options; but you can copy the translated text to the clipboard. Auto language-detection would be nice (for written translation, at least). 

Google Translate isn't perfect, but it seems to always be improving (at least I've noticed since first online). Yet again Google show their innovation and quality.

I can only judge this app by playing around with English to Spanish and Spanish to English since I am 100% fluent in both. First of all, the voice recognition blew my mind. In both languages it is the best I've encountered so far in any program. The translations are pretty good although they tend to be a bit too literal. 

What this app needs is the ability to "learn". This would require feedback from users to let the software know the accuracy of each translation. This way it can learn some common phrases and idioms that are currently being translated literally.  Learning is the way voice recognition has been mastered, the principle is the same.  I hope that more data is being entered on their end and I look forward to improvements.

It would also be nice if there was a way to record or create a voice memo of a translation that can be sent to others.  All in all, a very impressive app. Probably the best translator out there and it's FREE. iTranslate is very good and probably better for text translations but it can get expensive if you want the text read out loud in several languages. Also, I don't think it has voice recognition. This one does.  Thanks, Google!

column9: Couldn't ask for a better translator!!!
column10:
I am a Marine stationed in Japan, and If you're looking for a good translator, this is it! I use this app all the time when I go out to eat, shop or sight see.  I know a lot of the Japanese language already and I continue to learn more, and this definitely helps out a lot! It helps more if you have a constant Internet connection like a iPhone or a portable wifi device so you can use it on the go. What I like the most about it is that you're not restricted to a app's limited words or phrases. You type what you want to say, hit go and it translates it quickly! 

Most of the languages also supports audio too which is a big plus! The audio is very clear but could be a little slower. The Japanese is translated to either Hiragana or katakana, not sure which one, and in romanji which helps so you can read it yourself. 

The best part about this app is...it's FREE!!! After using this I feel robbed for buying the other Japanese language apps! Now if your trying to learn a language then get a app for that but this is a perfect translator! Thanks Google!!!ÓÄé

column9: Great app except for one major problem.
column10:
This app would be a fantastic travel tool except for one major problem, it requires a data connection. 

Many places lack data connectivity.  Even when data connectivity is available, using a third party SIM is nearly impossible for a carrier locked iPhone. Temporary overseas data plans are way overpriced for the average traveler.  Wifi?  Finding an open one on the run is nearly impossible.

I know Google is all about cloud computing. But, this is one app where a self contained model would make more sense. Google, you made one great app here. How about taking it one step further and making it a stand alone product.
And you can't go wrong with free.

It got almost all typed-in translations right, except into Yiddish (where it occasionally substituted English words, and made syntactic errors). 
It almost seems that instead of academic Yiddish, as codified by YIVO, Google used street-Yiddish from religious neighborhoods in Brooklyn. 

As for translation of spoken words (from those languages which have this feature) voice-recognition was only about 70% correct (maybe 
because I have a bit of an accent in all the languages I speak).   Let's hope that future releases will include a "learning  mode" independent of 
the localization setting of the iPhone.
